    {
      "turn_number": 1,
      "role": "interviewer",
      "type": "opening",
      "text": "Hello Angla, thank you so much for taking the time to speak with me today. I'm a researcher studying maternity care experiences, and I'm really interested in hearing your personal story. I understand you're in the early stages of pregnancy, and I'd love to hear about your experience in your own words. There are no right or wrong answers — I'm just here to listen and learn from you. Everything you share will help us understand how to make maternity care better. Shall we begin?",
      "question_id": null,
      "probe_id": null,
      "target_dimensions": [],
      "target_latent": [],
      "input_tokens": 0,
      "output_tokens": 0
    },
    {
      "turn_number": 2,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Yes, thank you for asking. I’m... nervous, honestly. I’m twenty-four, sitting in my tiny Newton apartment with the morning light way too bright and my neighbor’s coffee making me queasy — it’s silly how those little things pull me right back to that hospital memory. This is my second pregnancy and on paper it’s “low-risk,” but I live with the echo of eclampsia. I can still taste that metallic copper and the hospital lights are burned into me. Every time a nurse wraps that Velcro cuff around my arm I stop breathing for a second, waiting for something to go wrong.\n\nMy OB is kind, but there’s this distance. I read everything — blogs, studies, forums — trying to arm myself, but knowledge doesn’t erase the fear. I want to be excited, to think about names or a nursery, but mostly I’m trying not to spiral. I just want someone to see me as more than a chart; to say, “I hear you,” not just “you’re low-risk.” That would help more than anything right now.",
      "responding_to_question_id": null,
      "input_tokens": 771,
      "output_tokens": 486
    },
    {
      "turn_number": 3,
      "role": "interviewer",
