    {
      "turn_number": 18,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Mostly fear. It sits under everything—like a low hum that spikes every time my vision flickers or a cuff squeezes my arm. There are flashes of joy when I feel a tiny flutter or when I imagine a future kid, but they’re fragile and get swallowed quick. The memory of the seizure—those lights, the copper taste—comes back in a rush sometimes, and I feel stupidly guilty for being scared now that this pregnancy is “low-risk.” It’s hard to admit I’m not thrilled; I worry people will judge me.\n\nMy OB is kind, which helps, but the system doesn’t hold space for the panic. Appointments feel rushed, nurses are efficient but not always gentle with the emotional stuff. No one asked how the last experience left me; I had to bring it up and then felt like I was reminding them of something clinical, not lived. I ended up leaning on online groups and one close friend more than my care team for emotional support. What I want most is someone to say, “I hear that fear”—that kind of validation would make the fear less lonely.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "V2_PREG_Q03",
      "input_tokens": 1399,
      "output_tokens": 425
    },
    {
